     <br/>

      <p>
        So, the net force on the body of the x-direction is: 15 N - 17 N = -2 N
      </p>
      <p>
        The negative sign means that the net force on the body is 2 N in the <i>negative</i> x-direction (or to the left).
      </p>

      <hr/>

<br/>


     <br/>

      <p>
        <b>General definition of a "net" quantity. </b>In general, the "net" of something is the total amount
        in one "direction" minus the total amount in the opposite "direction." 
      </p>
      
      <p>
        <b>Other examples of "net" effects:</b>
      </p>

      <ul class="brm-list">
        <li>
          Another example is the "net" electric charge of atoms or molecules. This is the number of
          (positively-charged) protons minus the number of (negatively-charged) electrons. So, if an atom has 5
          protons and 7 electrons, the net charge would be -2.
        </li>
        <li>
          You might have heard of "net income" from your parents or other adults. That is the same idea: this means
          the total amount of money you earn minus the amount of money you pay in taxes.
        </li>
        <li>
          In football, the running back might run 10 yards forward, but see defenders coming and try to get around
          them by running backward 5 yards (toward the sideline, where there aren't any defensive players). If the
          runner gets tackled before he can start moving forward again, he has a "net gain" of 5 yards (10 yards
          forward - 5 yards backward).
        </li>
      </ul>

